summary.name: unemployment-across-industries
summary.dataset_description: Unemployment rates and counts across various industries from 2000 to 2010

properties.description: Number of unemployed individuals in the industry

goals.question: What is the overall trend of unemployment rate across all industries from 2000 to 2010?
goals.visualization: Line chart of unemployment rate over time
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand if the unemployment rate has been increasing or decreasing over the years and if there are any patterns or trends.

goals.question: Which industry had the highest unemployment rate in 2010?
goals.visualization: Bar chart of unemployment rate by industry in 2010
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us identify the industry with the highest unemployment rate in 2010 and compare it with other industries.

goals.question: What is the distribution of unemployed individuals across all industries?
goals.visualization: Histogram of count of unemployed individuals by industry
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the distribution of unemployed individuals across all industries and identify any outliers or patterns.

goals.question: How does the unemployment rate vary across different months of the year?
goals.visualization: Box plot of unemployment rate by month
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us identify if there are any seasonal patterns in the unemployment rate and if certain months have higher or lower unemployment rates.

goals.question: What is the correlation between the number of unemployed individuals and the unemployment rate?
goals.visualization: Scatter plot of count of unemployed individuals vs unemployment rate
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand if there is a correlation between the number of unemployed individuals and the unemployment rate and if the correlation is positive or negative.

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['date'])]
    data['year_month'] = data['date'].dt.to_period('M')

    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    sns.lineplot(x='year_month', y='rate', hue='series', data=data)
    plt.title('What is the overall trend of unemployment rate across all industries from 2000 to 2010?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Year-Month')
    plt.ylabel('Unemployment Rate')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.legend(title='Industry', loc='upper left')
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['date'])]
    data_2010 = data[data['year'] == 2010]
    industry_rate = data_2010.groupby('series')['rate'].mean().reset_index()
    max_rate = industry_rate['rate'].max()
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    ax = sns.barplot(x='series', y='rate', data=industry_rate)
    ax.axhline(max_rate, color='red', linestyle='--', label=f'Highest Rate: {max_rate:.2f}')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.xlabel('Industry')
    plt.ylabel('Unemployment Rate')
    plt.title('Which industry had the highest unemployment rate in 2010?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend()
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['date'])]
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    sns.histplot(data=data, x='series', hue='series', multiple='stack', palette='tab20', legend=True)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.xlabel('Industry')
    plt.ylabel('Count of Unemployed Individuals')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of unemployed individuals across all industries?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend(title='Industry', loc='upper right')
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['date'])]
    data['month'] = data['date'].dt.month

    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    ax = sns.boxplot(x='month', y='rate', data=data)
    ax.set_title('How does the unemployment rate vary across different months of the year?', wrap=True)
    ax.set_xlabel('Month')
    ax.set_ylabel('Unemployment Rate')
    plt.legend(title='Months', loc='upper right', labels=data['month'].unique())

    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):

    plt.title('What is the correlation between the number of unemployed individuals and the unemployment rate?', wrap=True)

    plt.ylabel('Unemployment Rate')
    plt.legend(title='Industry', loc='upper right', bbox_to_anchor=(1.25, 1))
